===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|lang=enm|secte}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|lang=fro|secte||a sect in philosophy or religion}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|lang=la|secta||a sect in philosophy or religion, a school, party, faction, class, gild, band, particularly a heretical doctrince or sect, etc.}}, possibly, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|lang=la|sequi||to follow}}.<!--Century 1911 has the derivation from "secare" as the main one through "secare viam" (take one's way, travel), discussing three alternative explanations as less probable: two of them from "sequi", one more from "secare". M-W online traces the origin to "sequi", so does Online Etymology Dictionary.-->

